<p>I’ve made changes to filter.js to handle different url hash components on the explore page.</p>
<p>The new version parses the hash component to extract parameters (genus, species, id, etc) and then uses the id to show the speciesinfo or if that is unavailable uses the genus+species parameters. The latter should make iNaturalist links work.</p>
<p>Warning. Because my fork is in a directory (/mdd/) rather than the root, I’ve had to change the paths in a number of files to get my fork functioning (i.e. change “/js/filter.js” to “js/filter.js”). I think these links should work when the code is in the root as on mammaldiversity.org. All the relevant changes for the permalink issue are in filter.js</p>
<p><em>Paper</em>: Ramírez-Chaves, H.E., Alarcón Cifuentes, M., Noguera-Urbano, E.A., Pérez, W.A., Torres-Martínez, M.M., Ossa-López, P.A., Rivera-Páez, F.A. and Morales-Martínez, D.M. 2023-05-30. Systematics, morphometry, and distribution of Eptesicus fuscus miradorensis (H. Allen, 1866) (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae), with notes on baculum morphology and natural history. Therya 14(2):299-311. doi:10.12933/therya-23-2290</p>
<p><em>Link</em>: https://www.revistas-conacyt.unam.mx/therya/index.php/THERYA/article/view/299</p>
<p><em>Suggested change</em>: Add <em>Eptesicus miradorensis</em> (H. Allen, 1866) as a species, encompassing some populations (Mexico to northern South America) that are currently in <em>Eptesicus fuscus</em>.</p>
<p><em>Additional references</em>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Yi, X.-l. and Latch, E.K. 2022-06. Nuclear phylogeography reveals strong impacts of gene flow in big brown bats. Journal of Biogeography 49(6):1061-1074. doi:10.1111/jbi.14362</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Comments</em>: As we discussed at ASM, GitHub issues could be a good way to bring up new papers or other suggested changes to the MDD. I’ll try this out for this paper and maybe some others I come across. If we like this format, we can set up some issue templates to make it easier to open the issue and standardize the format.</p>
<p>Now on to comments on the paper itself. This paper proposes recognizing the subspecies <em>Eptesicus fuscus miradorensis</em> as a species. I am not convinced, and in my database I plan to keep it as a subspecies for now (I’ll make it a species if MDD decides to accept it). Ramírez-Chaves et al. (2023) use only mtDNA (Cytb and COI). <em>E. f. miradorensis</em> is sister to all of <em>E. fuscus</em> in the Cytb tree, but sister to just <em>E. f. pallidus</em> (western USA) in the COI tree. Yi &amp; Latch (2022) also studied nuclear DNA and found a complex pattern of isolation and gene flow, but no especially distinctive position for <em>E. f. miradorensis</em>. Possibly more of the subspecies should be recognized as species, but to me the evidence looks more like a single species with a complex pattern of regional divergence. Addressed with commit 8cdf45784c17b54b51aff0920f1d584cd6895e7a Added json endpoint with commit 7fa08b3ae25bf78ba0da4ab4dc97a97d629dc9c7 Thank you for the resources and advice <span class="citation" data-cites="jhpoelen">@jhpoelen</span>.</p>
<p>My understanding of the motivation for revamping the site is to do exactly as you say and keep it as simple as possible so that it is maintainable into the future as others work on it. So I think doing our best to stick the html, css, and javascript to create a streamlined and static site is a good idea.</p>
<p>Man, there are a lot of libraries out there and it is very intimidating. Right now I am trying to figure out how to structure the site so that everything will work correctly. You had mentioned that you think keeping the database just as a csv is the easiest thing to maintain in to the future so I am figuring out how to search it. There is csv parse on npm and then papa parse seems fairly popular. If I can figure out how to integrate the parsers to populate fields (like an infographic when hovering or something) on the fly using javascript instead of having each species given their own dedicated page I think that will make it easier to keep everything simple and maintainable moving forward. That way the actual csv can change as much as it wants and be updated without having to generate or change a bunch of pages. But I could be wrong with my thinking there.</p>
<p>Thanks again for the resources. <span class="citation" data-cites="liphardt">@liphardt</span> great to hear that you are looking around for existing libraries to implement a basic search.</p>
<p>One thing to keep in mind is that a web page with statically inserted taxonomic information can be searched using selectors, effectively turning a webpage into a searchable dynamic document/database.</p>
<p>So, if you embed the taxonomic information tag attributes (e.g., <code>&lt;div class="Animalia Mammalia Homo sapiens"&gt;</code>), you can use the https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Element/querySelector with javascript or css selectors to implement some fancy looking show/hide/search behavior.</p>
<p>Luckily you probably won’t be the first to implement this behavior, because html/css/javascript/dom are widely used.</p>
<p>Good luck with the search and implementation! I am curious to see what you’ll come up with. Thanks <span class="citation" data-cites="jhpoelen">@jhpoelen</span> and <span class="citation" data-cites="liphardt">@liphardt</span> for the comments here – I’m on board with everything you both have written here. Schuyler demo’ed today some of the code he has been playing with and it looks good: fast, in browser searching using html tags, and starting to consider some javascript options. My only feedback for now is to push &amp; commit those changes more regularly, so that Jorrit can give feedback if / when appropriate. Thanks both! This is an with the BOM at the beginning of a UTF encoded CSV messing with how Ruby (Liquid) is parsing the first column. We temporarily fixed this by adding a blank first column. Leaving the issue open until a more permanent fix. Readme updated to reflect that you cannot have a BOM with 349b661906b392c8fdb29f069475145568bed761 Looks good! I resolved this issue with commit cd8ddb54c7f1f191b6c23ea7ccb05a258e5d923d. Added hidden column and updated the filter function. added with 10ac252bb61dbfd2c1adcc5da26ef63242b22951 Addressed with commit 7b1c52f07910690535981b8d8e6a9ca719703ce0 addressed with commit 7b1c52f07910690535981b8d8e6a9ca719703ce0 Okay. Keep me posted when the new spreadsheet is uploaded. Addressed with commit 178218be0fecdbde1c00c255fe1826d482e04cf4 <span class="citation" data-cites="jdhan39">@jdhan39</span> Let’s start here – some ideas for features: - Google maps zoom-able - Java script-based parsing from the MDD json file - Ideally filling in the values of country-level polygons using the ‘countryDistribution’ column only - Later can add subregions to the countries - Here is the metadata we have on the ‘countryDistribution’ field: <code>each country in which the species is extant or reintroduced into its native distribution is listed and separated by pipes (|); only the species native distribution or ancient introductions are included, whereas subjectively recently introduced populations in different countries are not included; countries in which the species is uncertainly present or possibly extinct are listed with a question mark (?) following the country; domestic species are listed as "Domesticated"; for fully extinct species, the distribution reflects the species distribution in the last 500 years (although this is somewhat subjective as well); for marine species, the countries in which the species is found along the coastline or in inland rivers are listed; when an 'and' is present within the countries name, it is listed using the ampersand (&amp;); dependencies are listed when geographically distant from there dependent country (see list below for specific examples); there are a number of city states and minor territories that are not included separately since most distributional data does not account for these regions, these include Andorra, Monaco, San Marino, the Vatican, Gibralter, Saint Pierre &amp; Miquelon, and any nearby islands or exclaves that are geographically close to the primary country or territory; the following is a list of the countries, dependencies, and territories listed as well as the spelling used for each: Greenland|Alaska|Canada|United States|Bermuda|Mexico|Guatemala|Belize|El Salvador|Honduras|Nicaragua|Costa Rico|Panama|Bahamas|Cuba|Jamaica|Haiti|Dominican Republic|Cayman Islands|Puerto Rica|United States Virgin Islands|British Virgin Islands|Turks &amp; Caicos|Anguilla|Saint Martin|Saba|Saint Barthélemy|Montserrat|Martinique|Guadeloupe|Sint Eustatius|Saint Vincent &amp; the Grenadines|Saint Kitts &amp; Nevis|Saint Lucia|Grenada|Barbados|Antigua &amp; Barbuda|Dominica|Aruba|Bonaire|Curaçao|Trinidad &amp; Tobago|Colombia|Venezuela|Guyana|Suriname|French Guiana|Ecuador|Galapagos|Peru|Brazil|Bolivia|Chile|Argentina|Falkland Islands|Kerguelen Islands|Prince Edward Islands|South Georgia &amp; the South Sandwich Islands|Saint Helena|Iceland|Norway|Sweden|Finlan