<p><span class="citation" data-cites="jts1882">@jts1882</span> <span class="citation" data-cites="n8upham">@n8upham</span> nice! Y’all are getting fancy with those tree views! A little tip - if you reference the issue number (e.g., <code>#24</code> or <code>https://github.com/mammaldiversity/mammaldiversity.github.io/issues/24</code>) as part of the commit message, then the changes will be automatically associated with the referenced issue. Apologies for the slow response, but I see you’ve got the treeview working.</p>
<p>I’ve restored the changes to filter.js in my fork (see Jan 24 post) with my solution to fix the permalink issue, that accepts urls with either id OR genus + species.</p>
<ul>
<li>The code parses the hash part of the url to get the parameters (order doesn’t matter)</li>
<li>If an id is available that is used. Any content in genus or species parameters is ignored and the link should continue to work if a species is moved to a different genus. This is the permalink.</li>
<li>If there is no id parameter, then genus and species are used. This should make the iNaturalist links function. An issue here is that as currently implemented, the the datafile is parsed twice so is even slower. This is not a permalink.</li>
<li>In addition it checks for a search parameter that can be used to populated the filter box, e.g.</li>
</ul>
<p>Examples:</p>
<p>Id alone: https://jts1882.github.io/mdd/explore.html#id=1006023</p>
<p>Genus+species: https://jts1882.github.io/mdd/explore.html#genus=panthera&amp;species=tigris</p>
<p>All three: https://jts1882.github.io/mdd/explore.html#genus=panthera&amp;species=tigris&amp;id=1006023</p>
<p>To list all the Felidae: https://jts1882.github.io/mdd/explore.html#search=Felidae</p>
<p>P.S. I’m still having issues with the relative urls and the root on my fork requiring an extra “/mdd/”). I had to change some links from “/js/filter.js” to “js/filter.js” in the .md files. However, the only changes to make the above work are in filter.js.</p>
<p><span class="citation" data-cites="jts1882">@jts1882</span> Very cool to see that you’ve gotten creative with the permalink issues. Are you planning to prepare a pull request also? I think it’d be great to have this information integrated in the https://mammaldiversity.org site. I’m cautious with the pull request as I’m still not sure about the urls relative to the root (see my PS above).</p>
<p>However, I think these show work in the mammaldiversity.org, so with that warning I’ll try and make a pull request. Antillomys rayi – I can’t remember why we included it as a recently extinct species (I think I remember seeing something from a paper saying that it was found with rat skeletons, but I haven’t checked); I’m retaining the species on our list for now; regardless, the name is actually unavailable for the time being, as its description appears in the supplemental material of the paper; its currently being redescribed by the authors in Therya (I reviewed the paper recently).</p>
<p>Megalomys camerhegne – with recently extinct species, I think I’ve been a lot less careful about which species I include and the since 1500 limit is kind of difficult to follow strictly. I’m going to add this species if you feel it is worth doing for consistency.</p>
<p>Archaeolemur edwardsi – I’m pretty confused on why I even included this species in the first place… I might remove it but I’m going to spend some time looking into it a bit more and remove that it was listed in MSW3.</p>
<p>Cordimus hooijeri – will go ahead and add the species as extinct: Zijlstra, J.S., McFarlane, D.A., Hoek Ostende, L.W. van den and Lundberg, J. 2014. New rodents (Cricetidae) from the Neogene of Curaçao and Bonaire, Dutch Antilles. Palaeontology 57(5):895-908. doi:10.1111/pala.12091</p>
<p>If you have any other recently extinct species you think should be included, definitely let us know. I have had a hard time keeping track of them.</p>
<p>Definitely agree that this is a tricky area since extinction cutoffs are necessarily arbitrary and for many species the date of extinction is not precisely established. Your precise inclusion criteria are obviously up to you, but my thinking is that the purpose of including extinct species is to give a better sense of what the full modern mammal fauna is like, including those species that were lost due to human action over the last few centuries. Therefore, it makes sense to err on the side of including additional species even if their exact extinction date is not firmly established. However, that does obviously mean more work in tracking literature on new species and radiocarbon dating.</p>
<p>In the Caribbean, you (and the Red List) include many species (e.g., <em>Nesophontes</em>, many echimyids and oryzomyines) based on subfossils because of evidence that they were found together with European-introduced rodents. I think it’s consistent to add <em>Antillomys</em> and <em>Megalomys camerhogne</em> (not <em>camerhegne</em>, misspelled it above), even if it’s not positively established those species survived past 1500. There are many other extinct species from the Holocene of the Caribbean (sloths, monkeys, bats, a few more rodents), but as far as I know they went extinct earlier. Reference for <em>camerhogne</em> is Mistretta, B.A., Giovas, C.M., Weksler, M. and Turvey, S.T. 2021-04-07. Extinct insular oryzomyine rice rats (Rodentia: Sigmodontinae) from the Grenada Bank, southern Caribbean. Zootaxa 4951(3):434-460. doi:10.11646/zootaxa.4951.3.2</p>
<p>On Madagascar, there are also lots of recently extinct species (<em>Cryptoprocta spelea</em>, many lemurs, a few bats and rodents, <em>Plesiorycteropus</em>, hippos). You include the fossa, two of the three hippos, and a few lemurs, but not the others. There is some C-14 dating and some rumors that some of these survived into historical times, but I’d have to do more reading to see if there’s solid evidence for any others making it past 1500. I agree and that’s why I’ve erred on the side of caution on many of them so far. But with my general focus on living mammals it’s been hard to keep track of just recently extinct mammals (my knowledge of mammalian fossil literature is much sparser than that of living species). For these Caribbean mammals, we summarized a lot of these extinction dates per island (last appearances) in our 2017 Annual Reviews paper: https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-ecolsys-110316-022754 – I’ll attach a PDF since Fig 2 is helpful visually.<br />
<a href="https://github.com/mammaldiversity/mammaldiversity.github.io/files/10542966/Cooke.et.al.-.2017.-.Anthropogenic.Extinction.Dominates.Holocene.Declin.pdf">Cooke et al. - 2017 - Anthropogenic Extinction Dominates Holocene Declin.pdf</a></p>
<p>I’ll also attach a CSV file from the Dryad download (https://datadryad.org/stash/dataset/doi:10.5061/dryad.tj4p5) that has those dates +/- error (sigma) <a href="https://github.com/mammaldiversity/mammaldiversity.github.io/files/10542967/fossil.csv">fossil.csv</a></p>
<p>Antillomys rayi is listed as 674 +/- 54 ybp according to MacPhee &amp; Flemming 1999 – which incidentally has a lot of other info on the last 500 years of extinctions: https://www.amnh.org/content/download/232397/4027716/file/Requiem%20Aeternam,%20The%20Last%20Five%20Hundred%20Years%20of%20Mammalian%20Species%20Extinctions.PDF</p>
<p>Here are my notes on the Jelle’s comments and changes within Chiroptera.</p>
<p>Nycteris vinsoni –&gt; N. macrotis comment – I’ll add Monadjem et al., 2010 as a reference.</p>
<p>Rhinolophus kahuzi -&gt; R. ruwenzorii Rhinolophus cohenae, R. mabuensis, R. smithersi -&gt; R. hildebrandtii Rhinolophus gorongosae, R. rhodesiae -&gt; R. simulator The Rhinolophus lumps are VERY tentative at the moment and may be reversed based on how discussions are going with Bat Names currently. Lumps were endorsed by Terry Demos and Bruce Patterson initially but paper is not discrete in their lumping of these taxa (although it is pretty heavily implied). So it might be pertinent to continue recognizing these species on Hesperomys until we’ve really decided on what to do with these taxa.</p>
<p>Coelops hirsutus &lt; C. robinsoni – I actually just lumped this species back into C. robinsoni based on comments from the Bat Names database, who don’t Heaney et al., 2016 provide enough (any) evidence for its species status (this is opposed to Rhinolophus hirsutus and Hipposideros antricola, which they agreed about recognizing based on the provided proof). So up to you about recognizing this form (I personally was pro-recognizing it based on biogeography, but I was out ruled in this case).</p>
<p>Balionycteris seimund &lt; B. maculata – I’ll go ahead and add Lim et al., 2017 to the reference</p>
<p>Doryrhina vs. Hipposideros (-) – I have now moved the six Indo-Australian species back to Hipposideros following discussion with the Bat Names database (I initially followed the HMW series, which moved the based on alleged relation to D. cyclops, but I now see that this wasn’t based on any other publications). I was not sure what to do with camerunensis, but I have kept it in Doryrhina since the Bat Names database does the same.</p>
<p>Hipposideros swinhoei vs. swinhoii (-) – I will probably change this to swinhoii in accordance with Hesperomys, although we should bring this up with Bat Names (they use swinhoei).</p>
<p>Hipposideros fasensis and H. parnabyi (+) – I’ve been torn about whether to recognize them or not, but because no data was given on why they were being recognized, I haven’t included them. Bat Names I think had them initially as species but also came to the conclusion of not recognizing them for now.</p>
<p>Hipposideros khasiana (+) – Nancy Simons and a few others at Bat Names agree with me that this name is certainly a nomen nudum and Nancy was able to contact the original descriptor of the name, who plans on republishing it with a designated holotype and full description now that we’ve given them a heads up on its nomenclatural availability. We all agreed that it is a valid species though and are looking forward to its redescription (they also have more specimens to work with for the species now!). I’ll add some clarifying comments on it.</p>
<p>Macronycteris vittata vs. vittatus (-) – probably going to change this to match Hesperomys, but need to check with Bat Names.</p>
<p>Miniopterus arenarius (+) and Miniopterus eschscholtzii and M. blepotis (+) – These changes have been contentious and we had a good bit of comments about it from Bat Names. I’m very skeptical about the species limits within these groups of Miniopterus, but given who the authors of the HMW chapter are, I decided to follow them, as they probably have knowledge I don’t about these clades. Plus, I think the Miniopterus schreibersii group is best with just giving this hypothesis on species designations for now. I think Bat Names has ultimately decided to recognize these species as well, but it was a split debate.</p>
<p>Chaerephon shortridgei (-) – I’m going to have to look at this more, but I’ll probably add it back given that Bat Names might be recognize it (as a species of Mops).</p>
<p>Micronomus, Ozimops, and Setirostris (+) – A similar thing happened with Macropus, which was split into Macropus, Osphranter, and Notamacropus, which I agreed on given the morphological disparities between these groups and the paraphyletic nature of Macropus with Wallabia (which I think also could’ve just been included under Macropus, but I like the current arrangement). Given that Mormopterus has a strange geographic spread, I like the recognition of the genera as distinct for now and Bat Names agrees.</p>
<p>Chaerephon vs. Mops – I actually disagree with Bat Names about recognizing Chaerephon as a subgenus of Mops, but the data does show that these to genera are not monophyletic with respects to the other (with one species being completely separate from the two genera). Hopefully these get resolved more adequately soon, but at this point I just follow Bat Names. They kind of did this with Neoromicia and Laephotis before that paper split the genera up into a number of genera, which I disagreed with at the time too, so Chaerephon and Mops may represent a number of diagnosable genera eventually too.</p>
<p>Molossus fluminensis and M. nigricans (+) – I think we’ll need to look into this more, but it seems like it holds up. I’ll keep the names for now but add a comment about castaneus probably being the oldest name for M. rufus and holosericeus for M. fluminensis. Definitely worth publishing if everything works out.</p>
<p>Nyctinomus vs. Tadarida and Nyctinomus thomasi (-) – I did not recognize these changes because of the general confusion surrounding Tadarida at this point, which seems to be a paraphyletic mess. Also, HMW doesn’t recognize these changes and neither does Bat Names at this point. However, I do think that Nyctinomus and Nyctinomus thomasi are worth recognizing if Bat Names agrees, so I will bring it up with them on our slack and see what they think.</p>
<p>Tomopeas ravum vs. ravus (-) – I will likely follow Hesperomys on this, but need to bring it up with Bat Names.</p>
<p>Anoura aequatoris and A. peruana (-) – I have now removed both of these species.</p>
<p>Artibeus vs. Dermanura and Koopmania (-) – I removed Koopmania recently, moving concolor back to Artibeus (Bat Names and no other source uses it). However, I would suggest using Dermanura, as Bat Names and most Neotropical bat researchers are recognizing it based on the consistent morphological distinctions between the two genera and their monophyletic nature. Dermanura has gone back and forth between publications and I think we should all try to be on the same page here so that it does become more normalized as the genus outside of the sphere of Neotropical researchers.</p>
<p>Gardnerycteris crenulata vs. crenulatum (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Lophostoma evote vs. evotis (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Vampyriscus nymphaeus vs. nymphaea (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Desmalopex leucoptera and microleucoptera vs. leucopterus (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Notopteris neocaledonica vs. neocaledonicus (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Nyctimene minuta vs. N. varius (+/-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names. I was actually the one who decided to move minuta to N. albiventer and seems like most people agree with it so far (wrote the accounts for Nyctimene in the HMW, Norberto Gianini approved). Kind of happy about that.</p>
<p>Pteropus gilliardi vs. gilliardorum (-) – I will leave this one for now, however, I’ve skimmed Dubois, 2007 and am starting to agree with that paper. This is going to be a bigger conversation when we get to Lepilemur…</p>
<p>Pteropus intermedius -&gt; P. vampyrus (+) – I actually prefer to retain P. intermedius and so does Bat Names apparently (still in discussion), so we might be adding this species back and I would recommend you retain it too for now.</p>
<p>Pteropus natalis (-) – I’ll add a comment about it, but I think Bat Names agrees not to recognize the species and I haven’t looked to hard into the taxonomy of this form yet.</p>
<p>Stenonycteris lanosa vs. lanosus (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Styloctenium mindorense vs. mindorensis (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Rhinolophus pumilus &lt; R. cornutus (+) – I reference Wu et al., 2012 as an example of a paper that doesn’t recognize it, although I should clear that up a bit. Gabor and I decided to recognize pumilus tentatively as a distinct species in HMW (I wrote the Rhinolophus accounts), but it was mostly based on morphology and the fact that the taxonomy of the group is a bit all over the place. Ultimately, I think many of the forms within this group may be conspecific based on low molecular divergence, but we’ll see.</p>
<p>Paratriaenops furcula – I’ll revise the comments.</p>
<p>Aeorestes/Dasypterus/Lasiurus (-) – We plan on removing this change at some point (I want to do it now, but Nate has wanted to wait until a publication we’re working on with Bat names is published). It consensus is just using Lasiurus, so definitely don’t recognize them as distinct genera.</p>
<p>Afronycteris nana vs. nanus (-) – I changed it to nana recently (my notes were switched on it though), so already done.</p>
<p>Eptesicus guadeloupensis and E. lynni (+) – I’m really hesitant to call all the Caribbean populations synonyms of E. fuscus, but based on recent work, a lot of people have decided to synonymize them. Eptesicus in the Caribbean needs a real revision because I do think they will end up distinct based on high divergence.</p>
<p>Eptesicus kobayashii -&gt; E. pachyomus (+/-) – I actually just added kobayashii back as a species for now based on conversations with Bat Names. There’s no papers that actually deal with the species taxonomy, so I am now tentatively retaining it and I would suggest you do too for now.</p>
<p>Glauconycteris curryi vs. G. curryae (-) – Again, won’t make the change for now but we’ll discuss this more…</p>
<p>Myotis ancricola and M. annatessae (-) – I’m retaining the species because of the lack of clarity about this in the paper (and see comments under the Rhinolophus lumps earlier). The other changes from the same paper were used because they directly reference making the changes.</p>
<p>Myotis australis (-) – I actually added this species back as well, so no need to change it.</p>
<p>Myotis niasensis -&gt; M. muricola (+) – I actually can’t remember why I haven’t used this change… Going to look into it more.</p>
<p>Neoromicia anchietae vs. N. anchieta (-) – I will likely go with Hesperomys on this one, but need to run it by Bat Names.</p>
<p>Plecotus christii vs. christiei (-) – I changed it back to christiei based on comments from Bat names that I’ll need to review. Stay tuned.</p>
<p>Baeodon (-) – made this change, although I moved Rhogeessa gracilis to the genus too based on more recent papers that suggest moving it to Baeodon too: Hoofer, S. R., &amp; Van Den Bussche, R. A. 2003. Molecular phylogenetics of the chiropteran family Vespertilionidae. Acta Chiropterologica, 5(Supplement), 1-63.|Volleth, M., Heller, K. G., &amp; Fahr, J. (2006). Phylogenetic relationships of three “Nycticeiini” genera (Vespertilionidae, Chiroptera, Mammalia) as revealed by karyological analysis. Mammalian Biology, 71(1), 1-12.|Baird, A. B., Hillis, D. M., Patton, J. C., &amp; Bickham, J. W. (2008). Evolutionary history of the genus Rhogeessa (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) as revealed by mitochondrial DNA sequences. Journal of Mammalogy, 89(3), 744-754.|Roehrs, Z. P., Lack, J. B., &amp; Van Den Bussche, R. A. (2010). Tribal phylogenetic relationships within Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) based on mitochondrial and nuclear sequence data. Journal of Mammalogy, 91(5), 1073-1092.|Roehrs, Z. P., Lack, J. B., &amp; Van Den Bussche, R. A. (2011). A molecular phylogenetic reevaluation of the tribe Nycticeiini (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Acta Chiropterologica, 13(1), 17-31.</p>
<p>Scotophilus borbonicus (-) – I also disagree with the Goodman paper and reverted this change.</p>
<p>Arielulus torquatus vs. Thainycteris torquatus (-) – This one is based mostly on the usage of the name in the HMW series and it looks that Bat Names agrees with the change for now. But I’ll need to look into it a bit more before I give a decision on whether to keep the change.</p>
