<p>I already made the change, so I think I’ll keep them lumped until MDD changes this back.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Coelops hirsutus &lt; C. robinsoni – I actually just lumped this species back into C. robinsoni based on comments from the Bat Names database, who don’t Heaney et al., 2016 provide enough (any) evidence for its species status (this is opposed to Rhinolophus hirsutus and Hipposideros antricola, which they agreed about recognizing based on the provided proof). So up to you about recognizing this form (I personally was pro-recognizing it based on biogeography, but I was out ruled in this case).</p>
</blockquote>
<p>OK, I’ll add it back. I also find it biogeographically plausible that this should be a species, but I feel like there’s not enough information to go against the experts.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Molossus fluminensis and M. nigricans (+) – I think we’ll need to look into this more, but it seems like it holds up. I’ll keep the names for now but add a comment about castaneus probably being the oldest name for M. rufus and holosericeus for M. fluminensis. Definitely worth publishing if everything works out.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Just to be clear, <em>castaneus</em> and <em>holosericeus</em> are both senior synonyms of <em>fluminensis</em> based on geography. <em>rufus</em> is older than any of these.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Nyctinomus vs. Tadarida and Nyctinomus thomasi (-) – I did not recognize these changes because of the general confusion surrounding Tadarida at this point, which seems to be a paraphyletic mess. Also, HMW doesn’t recognize these changes and neither does Bat Names at this point. However, I do think that Nyctinomus and Nyctinomus thomasi are worth recognizing if Bat Names agrees, so I will bring it up with them on our slack and see what they think.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I’ll await what the Bat Names people say.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Artibeus vs. Dermanura and Koopmania (-) – I removed Koopmania recently, moving concolor back to Artibeus (Bat Names and no other source uses it). However, I would suggest using Dermanura, as Bat Names and most Neotropical bat researchers are recognizing it based on the consistent morphological distinctions between the two genera and their monophyletic nature. Dermanura has gone back and forth between publications and I think we should all try to be on the same page here so that it does become more normalized as the genus outside of the sphere of Neotropical researchers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>OK, I’ll make <em>Dermanura</em> a genus since you’re confident this change will stick.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Eptesicus kobayashii -&gt; E. pachyomus (+/-) – I actually just added kobayashii back as a species for now based on conversations with Bat Names. There’s no papers that actually deal with the species taxonomy, so I am now tentatively retaining it and I would suggest you do too for now.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The HMW account for <em>pachyomus</em> did have some on-point comments about this name, but I’ll change it back to a species based on your comments.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Myotis ancricola and M. annatessae (-) – I’m retaining the species because of the lack of clarity about this in the paper (and see comments under the Rhinolophus lumps earlier). The other changes from the same paper were used because they directly reference making the changes.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I reread the paper and I feel they’re actually more definite about these two than the others. On p. 477 the say about <em>ancricola</em> and <em>annatessae</em>: "Compared to genetic distances observed in other _Myotis) bats, these taxa should be considered conspecific“. For <em>annamiticus</em> (p. 473) they only say”These pairwise comparisons were much below what is expected for inter-specific comparisons (Baker and Bradley 2006)", which seems less definite.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Baeodon (-) – made this change, although I moved Rhogeessa gracilis to the genus too based on more recent papers that suggest moving it to Baeodon too: Hoofer, S. R., &amp; Van Den Bussche, R. A. 2003. Molecular phylogenetics of the chiropteran family Vespertilionidae. Acta Chiropterologica, 5(Supplement), 1-63.|Volleth, M., Heller, K. G., &amp; Fahr, J. (2006). Phylogenetic relationships of three “Nycticeiini” genera (Vespertilionidae, Chiroptera, Mammalia) as revealed by karyological analysis. Mammalian Biology, 71(1), 1-12.|Baird, A. B., Hillis, D. M., Patton, J. C., &amp; Bickham, J. W. (2008). Evolutionary history of the genus Rhogeessa (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) as revealed by mitochondrial DNA sequences. Journal of Mammalogy, 89(3), 744-754.|Roehrs, Z. P., Lack, J. B., &amp; Van Den Bussche, R. A. (2010). Tribal phylogenetic relationships within Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) based on mitochondrial and nuclear sequence data. Journal of Mammalogy, 91(5), 1073-1092.|Roehrs, Z. P., Lack, J. B., &amp; Van Den Bussche, R. A. (2011). A molecular phylogenetic reevaluation of the tribe Nycticeiini (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Acta Chiropterologica, 13(1), 17-31.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>OK, I’ll put <em>gracilis</em> in <em>Baeodon</em> too. However, Baird et al. (2008:750), who found <em>gracilis</em> and <em>alleni</em> to be very close genetically, had some doubt that their specimen identifications were correct, and I don’t see discussion of <em>gracilis</em> in the two later papers (their trees just say “<em>Baeodon</em>”). Concerning the merger of Laephotis botswana with L. angolensis, I’d rather follow Monadjem et al. (2020), who still consider Laephotis botswanae to be a valid species.</p>
<p>Monadjem, A., Demos, T.C., Dalton, D.L., Webala, P.W., Musila, S., Kerbis Peterhans, J.C., Patterson, B.D. (2020). A revision of pipistrelle-like bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) in East Africa with the description of new genera and species. - Zool. J. Linn. Soc., 191 (4): 1114 - 1146 (for 2021) doi: 10.1093/zoolinnean/zlaa087</p>
<p>There also seem to be missing a few recently described species:</p>
<p><strong><em>Pseudoromicia mbamminkom</em></strong> Grunwald, Demos, Nguéagni, Tchamba, Monadjem, Webala, Kerbis Peterhans, Patterson and Ruedas, 2023. A review of bats of the genus «Pseudoromicia» (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) with the description of a new species. - Syst. Biod., 21 (1): 2156002.</p>
<p><strong><em>Pseudoromicia principis</em></strong> Juste, J., Torrent, L., Méndez-Rodríguez, A., Howard, K., García-Mudarra, J.L., Nogueras, J., Ibáñez, C. 2023. A new Pipistrelle bat from the oceanic Island of Príncipe (Western Central Africa). - J. Mamm. doi: 10.1093/jmammal/gyac110 ZooBank: 252DBECE-70A7-4FC6-BC1D-053569170FD5</p>
<p><strong><em>Rhinolophus chutamasae</em></strong> Soisook, P., Bates, P.J.J. 2022. Replacement name (nomen novum) for «Rhinolophus monticolus» Soisook et al., 2016. - Mammalia, doi: 10.1515/mammalia-2022-0012</p>
<p><strong><em>Rhinolophus namuli</em></strong> Curran, M., Kopp, M., Ruedi, M., Bayliss, J. 2022. A new species of horseshoe bat (Chiroptera: Rhinolophidae) from Mount Namuli, Mozambique. - Acta Chiropterologica, 24 (1): 19 - 40.</p>
<p><strong><em>Myotis barquezi</em></strong> Novaes, R.L.M., Cláudio, V.C., Díaz, M.M., Wilson, D.E., Weksler, M., Moratelli, R, 2022. Argentinean «Myotis» (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae), including the description of a new species from the Yungas. - Vertebr. Zool., 72: 1187 - 1216. Hey Victor <span class="citation" data-cites="VicVC">@VicVC</span>, I’m glad to see you commenting on this! I’ll provide some comments to your comments below.</p>
<p><em>Laephotis botswanae</em> - Is there any particular reason for not following the lump proposed by Taylor et al., 2022 (which also has Ara on the paper)? I though they made a pretty convincing case to lump <em>botswanae</em> into <em>L. angolensis</em> given the paraphyletic nature of their molecular data (although I would’ve liked to see more morphological evidence to make the revision more integrative). Taylor, P. J., Strydom, E., Richards, L., Markotter, W., Toussaint, D. C., Kearney, T., … &amp; Monadjem, A. (2022). Integrative taxonomic analysis of new collections from the central Angolan highlands resolves the taxonomy of African pipistrelloid bats on a continental scale. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 196(4), 1570-1590.</p>
<p>As for the other omitted species, thank you for bringing them up. This is based on a match between MDD and Hesperomys, so there area few that we both already have (<em>Rhinolophus chutamasae</em> and <em>Rhinolophus namuli</em>), but the other three (<em>Pseudoromicia mbamminkom</em>, <em>Pseudoromicia principis</em>, and <em>Myotis barquezi</em>) are on my list of species to add to the next MDD version (and I’m sure Jelle will add those species as well once we’ve gone through the current listing).</p>
<p>Also, I was wondering your personal perspective on the situation with African Rhinolophus that has been discussed in the Bat Names slack recently (I’m still going back and forth about whether to include or omit the various species suggested for lumping).</p>
<p>Hello Connor <span class="citation" data-cites="connorjburgin">@connorjburgin</span> , I stand corrected.</p>
<p>I still have quite a backlog of papers I need to go through in more detail and Taylor et al (2022) is one of these. Reading through this, I must agree that the two species should be lumped into <em>L. angolensis</em>.</p>
<p>I stayed away from the African <em>Rhinolophus</em> discussion in the Bat Names slack as I think this is still a very volatile situation, and I have no hands-on experience with this group. My feeling on this is that - as stated by Terry - given the lack of convincing data (pointing to either lumping or splitting) most (if not all) of these taxa should be considered separate species. Just wanted to briefly comment on some of these that remain unresolved:</p>
<p>Decisions Made:</p>
<p>Myotis ancricola and M. annatessae will stay on the MDD for now, given that the language used in the paper doesn’t explicitly lump either species into M. nepalensis, which is the same decision made by Batnames.</p>
<p>Thianycteris torquata will remain in Thainycteris rather than Arielulus based on morphological similarities to T. aureocollaris and the general consensus within the south-east Asian bat community that the two are included under Thainycteris together. Also, there was a recent paper that included both species in a molecular study, finding them to be sister species (see the recent Gorfol et al. papers, which I’m referencing on the MDD now): Görföl, T., Furey, N. M., Bates, P. J., &amp; Csorba, G. (2018). The identity of’Falsistrellus’ affinis from Myanmar and Cambodia and new records of Hypsugo dolichodon from these countries. Acta Chiropterologica, 20(2), 301-309.</p>
<p>I’m adding back all the Rhinolophus lumps from the Demos et al. paper because they didn’t explicitly decide to lump them (despite heavily implying it), and because Batnames will be continuing to include the species.</p>
<p>Decisions Pending:</p>
<p>Most of the spelling changes are being run by Batnames (Except for a few that I’m commenting under a different issue tab that I will not be excepting from Hesperomys)</p>
<p>Molossus fluminensis and whether castaneus has priority: I expect to keep this as fluminensis for now pending further research looking at the holotypes of each name, but we’ll see.</p>
<p>Nyctinomus + Nyctinomus thomasi - don’t expect these changes to be made by Batnames (which means MDD wouldn’t recognize them) since they were based on pretty small amounts of data, although there is a chance it’ll be recognized.</p>
<p>Thanks, I expect I’ll follow your lead on most or all of these. <span class="citation" data-cites="JelleZijlstra">@JelleZijlstra</span>, with regards to Vampyriscus nymphaea/nymphaeus, I can’t find anywhere that lists any form of ‘nymphaea’ like route from Greek or Latin as an adjective, all of them are listing them as nouns, so the correct spelling would be ‘nymphaea’ since that’s how it was spelt in the original description. Was wondering if you’d be able to provide further explanation and why you consider the name an adjective? http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dnumfai%3Dos</p>
<p><a href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/morph?l=numf-ai%3Dos&amp;la=greek&amp;can=numf-ai%3Dos0">νυμφ-αῖος</a> is an adjective meaning “of the nymphs”. In Latin it would be <em>nymphaeus</em>. This might be my inexperience with Greek and Latin showing, but how do we know it was based off the Greek root and not the Latin root? This is just on Wiktionary, but it says the Latin form is ‘nymphaea’ and is apparently a noun? https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/nymphaea#:~:text=Noun,species%20of%20the%20genus%20Nymphaea.</p>
<p>https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0059:entry=nymphaea I suppose there is a Latin noun <em>nymphaea</em> “water lily”, but it just seems a lot more plausible that Thomas would have named the species “of the nymphs” (a plausible association for a bat) than that he would have named it after a water lily for some unstated reason. The next species in the paper is named <em>thyone</em>, after a Greek minor deity (an alternative name for https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semele). That makes sense, thanks for the explanation! I agree with your logic, so I’ll treat it as an adjective. Almost done with MDD updates finally! Here are my responses by change.</p>
<p>Murexia melanura vs. melanurus (-) – I will follow the Hesperomys spelling.</p>
<p>“Murexia xenochromus” – wow, I hadn’t seen this but that definitely appears to be a hoax of some sort cause I’ve never seen that name (the page is now deleted so I wasn’t able to see it).</p>
<p>Myoictis wavica vs. wavicus (-) – although nobodies made this change, I agree with this change and think we should use the Hesperomys spelling.</p>
<p>Caluromysiops irrupta vs. irruptus (-) – because the name has not been around for 100 years without anyone using the alternate spelling, it should probably be changed. However, we might want to email Bob Voss and Sharon Jansa about it, as they might have some more to say about changing it. I’ll leave it on the MDD for now but add a comment.</p>
<p>Marmosa waterhousei vs. waterhousii (-) – I will make the change on the MDD to follow Hesperomys.</p>
<p>Dactylopsila kambuayai (though apparently it’s not extinct) – this is based entirely on the Handbook series, I think Ken Aplin (who recently passed away) is the one with proof that the species is still extant, but I think Stephen Jackson or Kris Helgen would be good people to ask about this further (I think I did ask Kris a while back but can’t remember his response).</p>
<p>Phalanger breviceps &lt; P. orientalis (though I haven’t yet seen the source) – Just sent you this.</p>
<p>Thylogale browni vs. brownii (-) – will follow Hesperomys on this.</p>
<p>Petaurus biacensis and P. papuanus (-/+) – This is definitely a difficult one, as I don’t think any of the three proposed options really make me feel comfortable. I chose to include it in P. notatus because I was working on a book for Lynx Edicions at the time, and including it in P. breviceps didn’t make sense biogeographically and P. notatus had a distribution up to Cape York, which was the closes to papuanus. However, after thinking about it for a while, I actually agree with you in recognizing papuanus as a species and giving strict indication of why we chose to do so for now, especially since molecular data shows that there are likely multiple species in New Guinea and that these forms are separate from Australian populations. I will add papuanus as a separate species, but I am retaining P. biacensis, as I can’t find any sources that synonymize the name at the moment.</p>
<p>Pseudochirops dahlii vs. Petropseudes (-) – Honestly, I’m pretty amazed that this hasn’t been followed by most subsequent authors, but it seems like there are multiple publications supporting this lump. I will follow this lump, but this is what Jackson and Groves 2015 say about it: “An assessment by Meredith et al. (2009a: 567) found Pseudochirops to be paraphyletic with respect to Petropseudes, grouping the latter more closely to Pseudochirops cupreus than to Pseudochirops archeri. As a result they suggested subsuming Petropseudes dahlii into Pseudochirops as Pseudochirops (Petropseudes) dahlii (Meredith et al. (2009: 567). We here retain the distinctive genus Petropseudes, but recommend revision of the entire subfamily to determine whether the monophyletic clades require recognition at generic level.” Meredith RW, Westerman M, Springer MS. A phylogeny of Diprotodontia (Marsupialia) based on sequences for five nuclear genes. Mol Phylogenet Evol. 2009a;51:554–571.| Meredith, R.W., Mendoza, M.A., Roberts, K.K., Westerman, M. and Springer, M.S. 2010. A phylogeny and timescale for the evolution of Pseudocheiridae (Marsupialia: Diprotodontia) in Australia and New Guinea. Journal of Mammalian Evolution 17(2):75-99.</p>
<p>Eulipotyphla vs. Lipotyphla (+) – Eulipotyphla has become the primarily used name for the group in most settings at this point, but much of the current literature is heavily influenced by our decision to use Eulipotyphla and the MDD and in the HMW series. This is what we put about ordinal names on the MDD’s about page, which highlights that Lipotyphla has been applied do various different inclusive definitions of different insectivore groups whereas Eulipotyphla is the first to apply to the modern interpretation of the order according to Woodman 2018: ‘Higher-level taxonomy.— Regarding higher-level taxonomy (i.e., all ranks above the species level), the MDD maintains an updated listing of all taxonomic ranks traditionally used below the order level as well as major superordinal clades. However, higher-level taxa do not yet have individual webpages, so this information is not yet fully transparent. For future updates, we intend to include individual taxonomic pages for each higher-level taxon in a similar format as the species-level pages. Ordinal names generally follow the arrangement presented in MSW3 with updates based on recent phylogenetic studies, resulting in Soricomorpha + Erinaceomorpha as Eulipotyphla, and Cetacea + Artiodactyla as a united Artiodactyla. The name Artiodactyla is preferred over the name Cetartiodactyla following the recommendation of Asher and Helgen (2010), which recalled the principles of Simpson (1945) to balance prevailing usage with priority in naming higher taxa. Asher and Helgen (2010) also recommended using Lipotyphla over Eulipotyphla, but confusion around the association of Lipotyphla with past definitions of the paraphyletic Insectivora assemblage (Woodman 2018) has prompted the MDD to favor Eulipotyphla as the first name used for the current definition of the order.’</p>
<p>Echinosorex gymnura vs. gymnurus (-) – given that Raffles name was lowercase, I think that retaining the name as an adjective would be more plausible. However, I’ll side with Hesperomys in this case and change the name to gymnura.</p>
<p>Otohylomys megalotis (-!) – I definitely appear to have just completely missed this (HMW doesn’t seem to have recognized it and I haven’t checked the reason why…), I’ll go ahead and make the move from Hylomys to Otohylomys: Bannikova, A.A., Лебедев, В.С., Абрамов, А.В. and Рожнов, В.В. 2014-06-04. Contrasting evolutionary history of hedgehogs and gymnures (Mammalia: Erinaceomorpha) as inferred from a multigene study. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 112(3):499-519. doi:10.1111/bij.12299</p>
<p>Crocidura anselli vs. ansellorum, greenwoodi vs. greenwoodae (-) – leaving it for now like the other ones, but we’ll have some further discussion on this.</p>
<p>Crocidura dongyangjiangensis and C. huangshanensis (+) – I’ll look into changing dongyangjiangensis from 2020 to 2019, but this might be a hard one to interpret.</p>
<p>Crocidura tarfayaensis vs. tarfayensis (-) – I’ll change the spelling to match Hesperomys on the MDD.</p>
<p>Chimarrogale vs. Crossogale (-) – I think I’ll go ahead and remove Crossogale again (I’ve gone back and forth about this one). I don’t agree with recognizing it either (Kai He and I made the decision not to include it in the HMW volume), but I had added it back after to the MDD for some reason.</p>
<p>Episoriculus vs. Pseudosoriculus (-) – I don’t think the HMW recognized it because we hadn’t seen the publication and we would have recognized it if we had seen the publication (either that or Kai He didn’t want to recognize it because he didn’t want to accept work from those authors). I strongly support recognizing Pseudosoriculus as a genus given the evidence.</p>
<p>Sorex monticolus vs. S. monticola (-) – I’m leaving this one for now because of just how many times I’ve gone back and forth about it, but I’ll clarify the comments about following Woodman 2018 on the spelling. I’m sure you’re probably right about this, but this one needs to be discussed further because it seems like nobody can decide which interpretation is correct.</p>
<p>Suncus varilla vs. S. varillus (-) – I’ll change the spelling to varilla following Hesperomys, I don’t really know why I even have varillus.</p>
