<p>Connor Burgin Ph.D. Student, Cook Molecular Evolution and Ecology Lab Department of Biology University of New Mexico</p>
<p>I’ll just jump in and say that revising McKenna and Bell would be an awesome resource for very many people — at its most detailed, it could take information from the Paleobiology Database (mostly at the specimen level) and then collapse that up into taxa with FAD / LAD and taxonomic / bibliographic / geographic information included. This is potentially a ton of work, but Hesperomys has laid the groundwork for this in a tangible way. I hare your all’s frustration at McKenna and Bell’s format when I was in grad school…</p>
<p>Downstream, having a full fossil + extant listing of mammals that was revised to higher taxon ranks would allow for an otherwise naive analysis of divergence timing using a Bayesian fossilized birth-death model and taxonomic / age constraints. A helpful target to keep in mind at least!</p>
